<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900817-0042</DOCNO><DOCID>900817-0042.</DOCID><HL>   What's News --   Business and Finance</HL><DATE>08/17/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1</SO><LP>   STOCKS AND BONDS sank on rising Mideast tension and moresigns of recession and inflation. The Dow Jones industrialsfell 66.83 points to close at 2681.44. Long-term Treasurybonds dropped 1 5/8 points. The bad economic news pushed thedollar to a new low against the mark. Gold futures pricessurged $6.60 an ounce.   ---</LP><TEXT>   Consumer prices rose 0.4% in July, putting inflation at a5.8% annual rate for 1990's first seven months, before oilprices soared. Meanwhile, housing starts fell for the sixthstraight month, dropping 2.6% to their lowest level since1982. The data show non-energy inflation persisting despiteeconomic weakness.   ---   Saudi Arabia and Venezuela intend to gradually boost theiroil output, by as much as 2.5 million barrels a day, whetheror not they win OPEC's approval at an emergency meeting thatthe two nations are seeking.   ---   Sears Roebuck plans to eliminate thousands of jobs in thenext several months, in an effort to cut annual expenses bymore than $100 million.   ---   James River plans to sell or close units with $1.3 billionin annual sales, nearly a fourth of the paper company. Thefirm will take a charge against earnings of about $150million.   ---   Cetus Corp.'s Robert Fildes quit as chief executive andpresident, two weeks after an FDA panel rebuffed the firm'scancer drug. Cetus also plans to lay off about 10% of itsstaff.   ---   CBS Records' Walter Yetnikoff agreed to step down as chiefexecutive of the Sony unit in two years.   ---   Exxon sued the IRS, challenging the agency's claim thatthe oil company owes $6.5 billion in back taxes. Exxon saidit expects to win but has set aside &quot;adequate&quot; reserves.   ---   Merrill Lynch and other firms are promoting a newtechnique for companies to cut their capital-gains taxes thatis the subject of IRS scrutiny.   ---   Saatchi agreed to sell McCaffrey andamp; McCall back to theunit's management for much less than the ad giant paid,people close to the deal said. The lower price reflectsSaatchi's desire to streamline itself, as well as bad timesfor ad agencies.   ---   Navistar posted a 79% drop in profit and a 10% decline inrevenue for the quarter that ended in July.   ---   Shearson agreed to accept less interest on a $500 millionloan to Prime Computer's parent in exchange for a biggerequity stake in the company.   ---   Ameritrust plans to cut 780 jobs, 11.5% of its work force.The bank company hopes to stem loan losses by reining in itsgrowth strategy.   ---   The New York Fed's backup power failed, delaying some banktransactions and securities trading.   ---   The FTC accused the nation's largest coin-assessment firmof making false and misleading claims.   ---   Canadian interest rates fell on the strength of thenation's dollar. The Bank of Canada's bank rate reached itslowest level since February.   ---   Austria will get nearly the same privileges inhigh-technology trade that the U.S. accords to allies.   ---   Markets --   Stocks: Volume 138,850,000 shares. Dow Jones industrials2681.44, off 66.83; transportation 939.78, off 21.90;utilities 202.59, off 2.58.   Bonds: Shearson Lehman Hutton Treasury index 3339.00, off47.31.   Commodities: Dow Jones futures index 134.67, up 0.51; spotindex 131.77, off 1.29.   Dollar: 147.25 yen, off 0.40; 1.5525 marks, off 0.0135.</TEXT></DOC>